{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17534726","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17534726"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:49:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:49:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15160"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15160","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15160"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.13,0.07,0.14,0.61]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7851"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108253"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7851","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7851"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15160"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90654"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"96"},{"type":"tags","id":"1519"},{"type":"tags","id":"1569"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"2705"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"3504"},{"type":"tags","id":"12910"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19145"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39714"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40404"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108253","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108253"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old woman is admitted to the Intensive Care Unit with diabetic ketoacidosis. She has type 1 diabetes mellitus diagnosed at age 12. Her regular medications are a basal-bolus insulin regimen. She developed gastroenteritis two days ago and has been unable to maintain oral intake since.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn initial arrival to the ICU she appeared unwell and dehydrated with a pulse rate of 120/min, blood pressure 85/50 mmHg, respiratory rate of 28/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Initial venous blood gas showed pH 7.0 (7.35-7.45), bicarbonate 6 mmol/L (22-28), and ketones 7.0 mmol/L (\u003C0.6). Capillary blood glucose was 32 mmol/L (4-8).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn review six hours later, she has now received 2.5 litres of intravenous crystalloid, an ongoing fixed rate insulin infusion and intravenous potassium replacement. She reports feeling much improved with a latest blood glucose of 12 mmol/L (4-8), but ketones remain elevated at 4.2 mmol/L (\u003C0.6).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Change to subcutaneous insulin","Commence bicarbonate infusion","Reduce insulin infusion rate","Increase insulin infusion rate","Add dextrose to intravenous fluids and continue insulin"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with severe diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA) triggered by gastroenteritis. The key principles of DKA management include fluid resuscitation, insulin therapy, electrolyte replacement, and regular monitoring. The main goal is to clear ketones, which requires ongoing insulin therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdd dextrose to intravenous fluids and continue insulin\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct management. When blood glucose falls below 14 mmol/L (guidelines may differ slightly), dextrose should be added to prevent hypoglycaemia while maintaining the insulin infusion to clear ketones. The insulin infusion is required to suppress ketogenesis and should not be stopped until ketones are cleared, even if blood glucose normalises.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduce insulin infusion rate\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as ketones remain significantly elevated. The fixed rate insulin infusion should continue until ketones are less than 0.6 mmol/L, regardless of blood glucose levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncrease insulin infusion rate\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated as the current rate appears to be working effectively with improving blood glucose and ketones. Increasing the rate could lead to rapid glucose lowering and potential complications such as cerebral oedema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChange to subcutaneous insulin\u003C/strong\u003E is premature. Transition to subcutaneous insulin should only occur once ketosis has resolved (ketones \u003C0.6 mmol/L) and the patient is eating and drinking.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommence bicarbonate infusion\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated in DKA unless there is severe acidosis (pH \u003C6.9) or life-threatening hyperkalaemia. The acidosis will continue to correct with appropriate fluid and insulin therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Fixed rate insulin infusion should be continued in DKA until ketosis is cleared, even if blood glucose normalises.","When blood glucose falls below 14 mmol/L in DKA, dextrose should be added to intravenous fluids while continuing insulin therapy.","Resolution of DKA is defined by normalisation of ketones (\u003C0.6 mmol/L), not blood glucose levels."],"references":["Lizzo JM, Goyal A, Gupta V. Adult Diabetic Ketoacidosis. [Updated 2023 Jul 10]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK560723/","Evans K. Diabetic ketoacidosis: update on management. Clin Med (Lond). 2019 Sep;19(5):396-398. doi: 10.7861/clinmed.2019-0284. PMID: 31530688; PMCID: PMC6771342."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90654"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15160"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90654","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90654"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-08T19:58:27+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-08T19:58:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7851"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108253"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"26","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/26"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd7c","name":"Critical Care Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","link